Rokenbok Parts + 3D Virtual Library + Your 3D Printer = 3D Printing and Solid Modeling Lab!

In collaboration with Kid*Spark, Rokenbok is making every tangible part in the Rokenbok System available as ready to print virtual files. Students, educators and avid Rokenbokers can design, modify and create 3D parts that expand the Rokenbok System.

Teachers can use this resource in collaboration with Rokenbok Education curriculum to give students a real engineering experience and expose young students to the world of 3D printing and solid modeling.

The 3D Virtual Library has three segments:
• Library parts - construction parts from 20 years of Rokenbok development, now free for everyone.
• Custom parts - enable Makers to create new types of mechanisms and machines, download and print! Universal joints, bearings, and more.
• Customizable parts - can be modified by anyone–no 3d modeling experience required!

I'm a critical maker, I call myself 'cirujadigital' (ciruja is a word we use in argentina to name homeless wich pick up things from garbage). Technology is not neutral,neither maker movement. I think that maker movement must be understood in a context of technological and social changes, also known as cognitive capitalism. Even more, there are important diferences in maker movement in different countries related to path dependence, history, center-periphery issues, etc. These differences affect the way we motivate to do things, not just solving problems vs hedonism, but also the way we reflect about the whole maker movement. As a movement that officially revindicates its heritage from open software, hackers and counter cultural movements, maker movement and open hardware seems to be loosing these cultural bases today. Behind the maker movement lies the potential to make a real revolution...or just another corporative maker-market. We must build a real community-based maker movement, with multiple voices and reflections, before it becomes another middle class fetish. Real democratization and revolution is in our hands...what we will do?

bio:
I'm a software and hardware engineer. My work is at several small entrepreneurial companies, and my play is making.

I used a Cube for a year, and then switched to a SeeMeCNC Orion. It's like going from Apple to IBM circa 1990 - a completely closed platform that doesn't do the cool things but does the regular things well and reliably, vs. a completely open platform that takes some setup but can do anything you like and allows you to solve problems as they come up. Since then I built a Rostock Max v3, which is the Orion's bigger and newer sibling.

I'm currently playing with SeeMeCNC's 2 Into 1 Dual Filament Feed Adapter, and it's been... interesting.

Greetings,

I've been messing with electronics software and computers all my life. Built a SWTPC 6800 at age 18. A friend and I drove to the twin cities (Minnesota) to look for computer stores. There were just a couple in 1977/78. I've worked as a software developer and an electronics technician in the past. Now I work in the medical field -- a change of pace and all the rest is now a hobby--It's a lot more fun that way. I've got a few apps available for IOS, and have been enjoying working in Unity3d. Discovered 3d printing about a year or so ago after stumbling upon James Bruton on Youtube (xrobots.co.uk) making a 3d printed Alien Cosplay suit. While I'm not particularly interested in Cosplay or movie props, James has and continues to do very interesting and imaginative things with 3d printing. I ended up purchasing a Lulzbot Kittaz. . Truly enjoyed putting together a kit again, too bad they don't sell a kit version of their printer anymore. I'm very excited about the possibilities of 3D printing. Congratulations if you've made it this far - apparently you need a 3d printer. Also check out some of my web pages including markziemer.net - my personal website with vacation photos, or markziemerapps.com for my iOS apps.
